âœ… Comments

Comments are little notes you write inside your code that the computer ignores.
They are meant for humans, not machines.

// This is a comment. It explains what the code does.

Why we use them:

They help you remember what your code does.

They help other people understand your code.

They help AI assistants (like Copilot!) know what you want.

Think of comments like:

ğŸ§¡ Sticky notes in a book
ğŸ§¡ Directions written on your LEGO set
ğŸ§¡ Notes to your future self

âœ… Variables

A variable is a box that holds information.

let score = 0;    // put 0 into a box called "score"
score = score + 1;   // update the box with a new value

Why we use them:

To store things your program needs to remember (score, clicks, time).

To make your game change over time.

Think of variables like:

ğŸŸ¦ A bucket with a label
ğŸŸ¦ A save slot in a video game

âœ… Functions

A function is a mini-program inside your program.

function addScore() {
  // steps that run when the function is called
}

Why we use them:

They keep code organized.

They prevent repeating the same code everywhere.

They let buttons and events trigger actions.

Think of functions like:

ğŸ³ A recipe
ğŸ“¦ A set of instructions you can use again and again

âœ… Event Listeners

Event listeners make your code react to things happening on the page.

button.addEventListener("click", addScore);


This means:

â€œWhen someone clicks this button, run the addScore function.â€

Why we use them:

They make your project interactive!

Buttons work, games run, animations start, timers tick.

Think of event listeners like:

ğŸ‘€ A referee watching the game
ğŸ® A controller button being pressed

